  "translation_keys": {
    "variance": "Variance"
  },
  "short_description": "Principal Component Analysis for dimensionality reduction (supports multiway data via U-PCA)",
  "long_description": "Performs Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to reduce data dimensionality while retaining maximum variance. Supports both univariate (2D) and multiway (3D+) data using U-PCA (Unfolded-PCA). PCA transforms correlated variables into a set of uncorrelated principal components.\n\nHow It Works:\n- Calibration data (X_cal) is used to compute principal components\n- Components are ordered by explained variance (highest first)\n- Loadings show how original variables contribute to each component\n- Scores are the transformed data in the new component space\n- Validation data (X_val) is projected using the same loadings\n\nMultiway Data (U-PCA):\n- For 3D+ data: keeps sample dimension (axis 0) intact\n- Unfolds all other dimensions into single variable dimension\n- Example: (100 samples, 50x10 variables) -> treated as (100, 500)\n- Returns 'data_shape' field for reference: (100, 50, 10)\n- Loadings in unfolded space: (500, n_components)\n- Allows PCA on spectroscopic imaging or multi-sensor data\n\nKey Concepts:\n\n1. Principal Components\n   - Orthogonal (uncorrelated) directions of maximum variance\n   - First component captures most variance, second next most, etc.\n   - Ordered by importance\n\n2. Loadings\n   - Weights showing contribution of original variables to each component\n   - Reveal which variables drive each component\n   - Shape: (n_variables x n_components) or (unfolded_vars x n_components) for multiway\n\n3. Scores\n   - Data projected onto principal components\n   - New representation of samples in component space\n   - Shape: (n_samples x n_components)\n\n4. Variance Explained\n   - Percentage of total variance captured by each component\n   - Helps decide how many components to retain\n   - Cumulative variance shows total explained by selected components\n\n5. Reconstruction Error\n   - RMSE when reconstructing original data from scores and loadings\n   - Indicates information loss from dimensionality reduction\n   - Lower values mean better reconstruction\n\nNumber of Components:\n- Start with 2-3 for initial exploration\n- Use scree plot to identify \"elbow\" point\n- Consider cumulative variance explained (typically 80-95%)\n- More components = better reconstruction but less dimensionality reduction\n- Fewer components = more reduction but more information loss\n\nCross-Validation Mode:\n- With CV enabled: calculates per-fold components and scores\n- Useful for assessing model stability\n- Helps select optimal number of components\n- Without CV: Single fit on full calibration data\n\nAdvantages:\n- Unsupervised (doesn't require response variable)\n- Interpretable through loadings and score plots\n- Removes collinearity among variables\n- Can preprocess data for downstream modeling\n- Useful for data visualization (2-3 components)\n- Computationally efficient\n- Works with multiway data (U-PCA)\n\nLimitations:\n- Components are linear combinations (nonlinear PCA available separately)\n- May not find components relevant to prediction task\n- Sensitive to data scaling (consider centering/normalization)\n- Interpretation requires domain knowledge\n- May require many components for complex data\n\nUse When:\n- Exploring data structure and relationships\n- Reducing computational load for downstream models\n- Addressing multicollinearity issues\n- Visualizing high-dimensional data\n- Preprocessing for other models (PCR, PLS)\n- Identifying key variables (via loadings)\n- Analyzing spectroscopic imaging data (multiway via U-PCA)\n\nNext Steps:\n- Use scores as input to regression models (PCR)\n- Plot scores to visualize samples\n- Analyze loadings to identify important variables\n- Compare with PLS for supervised dimensionality reduction\n- For multiway: reshape loadings back to original variable structure\n\nTip: Center and normalize data before PCA to ensure all variables contribute fairly to components.",
  "execution_report_specs": {
    "messages": {
      "upca_used": "Higher-order input data was unfolded and processed with U-PCA."
    },
    "warnings": {
      "discrete_axis_recommend_autoscale": "Discrete axis nature was detected. For PCA, autoscaling is usually recommended so discrete-coded variables do not dominate component variance by scale alone. Consider applying Center and Scale with method 'autoscale' before PCA."
    },
    "errors": {}
  },
